    {
      "note_no": "48",
      "note": "The Qur'anic term la'nah - usually but inexactly translated as \"curse\" (and popularly used in this sense in post-classical Arabic parlance) - denotes \"banishment\" or \"alienation\" (ib'ad), i.e., from all that is good (Lisan al-'Arab). Whenever it is attributed in the Qur'an to God with reference to a sinner, it signifies the latter's \"exclusion from God's grace\" or his \"rejection by God\". In the present context, this meaning is reinforced by the subsequent reference to \"a most evil fate\" (lit., \"abode\") in afterlife. - For an explanation of the phrase \"what God has bidden to be joined\", see note 43 above."
    }
  ],
